<solution><div><h3><alert>Worked solution</alert></h3>
<p>Given <m> \displaystyle z={0} + {4}i</m>, let's express <m>z</m> in polar form:</p>

<ol>
  <li><p>Magnitude (<m>r</m>) of <m>z</m>:</p>
    <m>\displaystyle r = \sqrt{({0} )^2 + ({4})^2} = \sqrt{{0} + {16}} = \sqrt{{16}} = {4} </m></li>
  <li><p>Argument (<m>\theta</m>) of <m>z</m>:</p>
    <m> \displaystyle \theta = \arctan\left(\frac{\text{Im}(z)}{\text{Re}(z)}\right) = \arctan\left(\frac{{4}}{{0}}\right) </m>
    <m>\displaystyle  \theta= {\frac{\pi}{2}} \approx {1.57}</m></li>

 <li>
<p>Now, <m>z</m> in polar form becomes:</p>
<m>\displaystyle  z = re^{i\theta} = {4}e^{{\frac{\pi}{2}}i} ={4 \mathrm{i}}</m>

</li>
 <li>
<p>Expressing the square root of <m>z</m> in polar form:</p>
<m>\displaystyle  \sqrt{z} = \sqrt{ {4}}e^{{\frac{\pi}{2}}i}=\sqrt{{4 \mathrm{i}}} </m>
 <p>Now, for possible values of  <m>\displaystyle  \sqrt{z} ,</m> we consider the fact that the square root function introduces a <m> \pm </m> sign:</p>

<p><m>\displaystyle  \sqrt{z} = {2 \left(\frac{\mathrm{i}}{\sqrt{2}}+\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}\right)} </m> or </p>
<p><m>\displaystyle \sqrt{z} = {2 \left(-\frac{\mathrm{i}}{\sqrt{2}}-\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}\right)} </m></p></li></ol></div></solution>
<answer><p><m>2 \left(\frac{\mathrm{i}}{\sqrt{2}}+\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}\right)</m></p></answer>
<answer><p><m>2 \left(-\frac{\mathrm{i}}{\sqrt{2}}-\frac{1}{\sqrt{2}}\right)</m></p></answer>
